  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 14:14-15",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Chronicles 14:14-15",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They smote all the cities round about Gerar — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Partly because they had joined with Zerah in this war, and partly because the Ethiopians had sheltered a great part of the remains of their army in them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "For the fear of the Lord came upon them — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That is, God struck them with such a fear, that they had no heart to withstand, or even to make any resistance against the conquerors. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They smote also the tents of cattle — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That is, the dwellers in tents, who were either a part of Zerah’s company, or joined with them, or had come along with them, to furnish that great host with necessary provisions. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And carried away sheep and camels — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Fetched them away out of the enemy’s country in vast numbers. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "14:1-15 Asa's piety, He strengthens his kingdom. - Asa aimed at pleasing God, and studied to approve himself to him. Happy those that walk by this rule, not to do that which is right in their own eyes, or in the eye of the world, but which is so in God's sight. We find by experience that it is good to seek the Lord; it gives us rest; while we pursue the world, we meet with nothing but vexation. Asa consulted with his people how to make a good use of the peace they enjoyed; and concluded with them that they must not be idle, nor secure. A formidable army of Ethiopians invaded Asa's kingdom. This evil came upon them, that their faith in God might be tried. Asa's prayer is short, but it is the real language of faith and expectation from God. When we go forth in God's name, we cannot but prosper, and all things work together for the good of those whom he favours.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
